Hi Quizizz Educator,



This is to inform you about the upcoming Google Workspace for Education
policy changes that may impact your students' ability to access Quizizz
after *October 23, 2023*.

Here is everything you need to know to avoid interruption in your Quizizz
experience due to these changes.



*Who is impacted?*



If your school has school-administered Google accounts for students, you
may be impacted by Google’s changes. *However, this does not impact you if
your school does not use school-administered Google accounts for students.*



*What’s happening?*



Starting October 23, 2023, Google Workspace for Education is changing its
privacy settings. Google users designated as under 18 won’t be able to use
their school-administered Google credentials to access teacher-favorite
tools like Quizizz unless a Google Workspace administrator takes action.



*What do I need to do?*



To avoid potential disruption for your students, it’s critical that your
school marks Quizizz as trusted in Google Workspace for Education.

Hi Quizizz Educator,



This is to inform you about the upcoming Google Workspace for Education
policy changes that may impact your students' ability to access Quizizz
after *October 23, 2023*.

Here is everything you need to know to avoid interruption in your Quizizz
experience due to these changes.



*Who is impacted?*



If your school has school-administered Google accounts for students, you
may be impacted by Google’s changes. *However, this does not impact you if
your school does not use school-administered Google accounts for students.*



*What’s happening?*



Starting October 23, 2023, Google Workspace for Education is changing its
privacy settings. Google users designated as under 18 won’t be able to use
their school-administered Google credentials to access teacher-favorite
tools like Quizizz unless a Google Workspace administrator takes action.



*What do I need to do?*



To avoid potential disruption for your students, it’s critical that your
school marks Quizizz as trusted in Google Workspace for Education.

Share our *help center article
<https://link.learn.quizizz.com/ls/click?upn=l2rvzz6Ge9DeOyh1KLX-2BjvEw20ZYjIpcyUgSP0qsBBaMZSX5qZqaLDJjIYMZXDFtn91zcUKXA4ExgCUGe2rWoIZZWHhYfPWz2UylLD2yStqsAxkQD6YqgARuWOXyoNk5Wq02DiwlalXZg1pPqtJdBqZlS5iDXM6Zs3pbEBu-2FTYI0nfCdE3-2FxQZqWbxObXgLi86AGfbvm5jYTO36PebzBFr-2FYwYlzHVhvOrSi9t-2FK2Bk-3DK-Li_bnj1YW-2Bp4pnNDQIMu1dpy4rNSJ0kh35KLN5IYzOW1awjIvwxoaiG809xy7oTGMWiwepFGXDeAz6OH4NKZOKhxF9ZSCaPVpwjzTcpR0e4EFfB-2BmWiwISwAu-2FXju8kapujxEke1lcxVyEKRSFncm2hMGAuqexJWoPGfJiXyvwMdvzrZOSdLLcC6-2BYGwl0BDvhuGXkF6sLvOwoNcxyREGWqXi0bAVR46YsQ83VGFx3l21-2F2oIItl3U-2F4DlQYsKHqoLlRWoXUI3aINVZJFuqhaCn7LeZ9ljRRsVVF-2Bv2fpO7Onqn2BpRwoDMTBbh6iDECN7EdfDdQ-2B-2Fqna-2FrQ-2BQovwK35J3stO77hHA2P0elvzZgY8eY-2FCGThJAGTkeRIl2Vkr13tuJJDPW6Y3hy74yZiFX6sbTqhG40Sa1uZNBwljILU58eq-2Bdrq8xfw1aOos03vgsJUx-2Fy7J88nlIspYdh9XJBIeeDLDQnQGVu6GAUCYi3GKWsJWD9PoU8FcEPfHKxRJWnFeY7RyTqcSdUzL8Fi6A-2B6cKbjmeTpgBCb7Gr3hNxRWx5nmHmUZzxVuD4dQuB-2FQ3xUXjEpTX9UEgzYcGKlfZxFqaQnbBs7c9Jv5iRoh01ZNJXFV6yUOXnECZU3-2FUbVuGGcl92aQrDnWO0X5UMd6MPTw-3D-3D>*
with your school IT department to ensure your students can log into Quizizz
with their school-administered Google credentials. Only the Google
Workspace for Education administrator can mark Quizizz as trusted.



*Is anything changing about Quizizz? *



Quizizz is not changing any of our policies. *Students can always join a
quiz or lesson through an internet browser without signing in using their

Hi Quizizz Educator,



This is to inform you about the upcoming Google Workspace for Education
policy changes that may impact your students' ability to access Quizizz
after *October 23, 2023*.

Here is everything you need to know to avoid interruption in your Quizizz
experience due to these changes.



*Who is impacted?*



If your school has school-administered Google accounts for students, you
may be impacted by Google’s changes. *However, this does not impact you if
your school does not use school-administered Google accounts for students.*



*What’s happening?*



Starting October 23, 2023, Google Workspace for Education is changing its
privacy settings. Google users designated as under 18 won’t be able to use
their school-administered Google credentials to access teacher-favorite
tools like Quizizz unless a Google Workspace administrator takes action.



*What do I need to do?*



To avoid potential disruption for your students, it’s critical that your
school marks Quizizz as trusted in Google Workspace for Education.

Share our *help center article
<https://link.learn.quizizz.com/ls/click?upn=l2rvzz6Ge9DeOyh1KLX-2BjvEw20ZYjIpcyUgSP0qsBBaMZSX5qZqaLDJjIYMZXDFtn91zcUKXA4ExgCUGe2rWoIZZWHhYfPWz2UylLD2yStqsAxkQD6YqgARuWOXyoNk5Wq02DiwlalXZg1pPqtJdBqZlS5iDXM6Zs3pbEBu-2FTYI0nfCdE3-2FxQZqWbxObXgLi86AGfbvm5jYTO36PebzBFr-2FYwYlzHVhvOrSi9t-2FK2Bk-3DI17N_9urzpVnn3Qnlr4n9Y5pDOs0frxQUsJGfQaYcl4OhGW16A1Lg95-2FemQn-2BsZnSAFOp2aPtRX8Y-2FhVeVyV9osPNlD9rWHdWH1-2FHY4W6I0MZr0OKc7uswKofCfj0c8eku1opPV8dXX2-2Fur7v6PvQmy6Fp05WVYmkRbZDsl5pG-2FVBXinDNoLJlKscn1byFRmOaMJCRN9jxlVuQkG-2Ft2lND7hNJXAjLSNOMQ5Ybi6fgDRpM50veTfUP1ByxFTb0P2P7qKISv7WdqO6VSxXb0xbq412H0btsQZv0m9N9QQLsFpw8FAiY-2B89AZPIk36KVZSifOG62g55w22Ed9RFVfR8pFGsH9SFqe0IalnMqm8YQrzZFHDzI-2BuLM66VDAt3mmziTOIUa8ddQ-2FMotEST3yt2QdTai4n3LFSSTGJTx7GP3vdCxUhFqkKxg8FwKS0pYX38jluXksMGzxivyv0JGQu1KbdOf2IFGGch3XQju1wLENNfi38PaCKD1wDLg6ejnM7HxGXgYEsDwGMuKflLiNrBLyYiPYwEgzZJuqTeTfzbN3pLa2Xp1ac1uITTDDDJyCDVq7hEvOUOAKY97iGUEqKhMlDRVRG0NLNyjo1Z8EOGDSGRbzfjss1-2BxAFmY4Z5YqcDGo1bJdxwIAwvaxZ0dm7NaWEZ-2FQ-3D-3D>*

We are reaching out with an important update regarding Google SSO.

applications (including Screencastify) for students under the age of 18
unless the admin confirms access in the Google Admin Console.

by October 23, 2023, or your organization may lose access to Screencastify.
Follow these i**nstructions for Confirming Screencastify as a Trusted App
for Google SSO:*



1. Log into Google Admin Console as an administrator

2. Navigate to the App access control card.

3. Click Review apps and select Screencastify.

4. Click Configure access.

5. Confirm Screencastify is set to Trust. Review the confirmation
information, then click Confirm.

Hi Chris,

ACTION REQUIRED: Review and confirm your third-party app settings for
Screencastify by October 23, 2023 in the Google Admin Console, or your
organization may lose access to Screencastify.



We are reaching out with an important update regarding Google SSO.



To protect student data privacy, Google will restrict access to third-party
applications (including Screencastify) for students under the age of 18
unless the admin confirms access in the Google Admin Console.



*Admins need to ensure Screencastify is marked as a trusted app in Google
by October 23, 2023, or your organization may lose access to Screencastify.
Follow these i**nstructions for Confirming Screencastify as a Trusted App
for Google SSO:*



1. Log into Google Admin Console as an administrator

2. Navigate to the App access control card.

3. Click Review apps and select Screencastify.

4. Click Configure access.

5. Confirm Screencastify is set to Trust. Review the confirmation
information, then click Confirm.

For more information, check out our Help Center article
<https://ww2.screencastify.com/r?i=castify&e=cbr33kh4czjisz5ozyudazjjngun25mbhkixi4yctinnbfotfxyq6pvcrtzw5eaqozc5rzfqfxge5fgoya2yfdfrwq653vwpzldyngy7wbkz33puhcvdtjt4err7zos3s2jexvhh72cy3w57zkynkr6dtq6xmvoynxhhuhc7ljexzrdcjfkny7qkssweduazwcqnfzeicvszq4tmyr6swqnl3m>

*Year-end statement: urgent action required*

*Why we’re contacting you*

We did not receive your school’s year-end statement for the National
Tutoring Programme (NTP) by the deadline last week.


We are aware that some users had difficulties accessing the form and we
thank you for your patience.


We have now fixed the issue and reopened the form to give you a final
opportunity to submit.



You must submit the year-end statement
<https://news.service.education.gov.uk/10A62B4FA25F9B74CDC17420D8414C867AFFFE4EBC625C25445C70474DE43D4E/7D264052E307D54846A037BDA1E04A19/LE35>
as soon as possible, and by no later than *2pm on Thursday** 12 October.*

This is a hard deadline and failure to submit your form will result in your
full funding allocation being recovered by the ESFA. You must complete the
form even if you did not use any of your NTP funding.


If your school converted to an academy after 1 August 2023, you’ll need to
select your old establishment and URN when completing the form, rather than
your new one.

We’ve published guidance on how to submit your year-end statement
<https://news.service.education.gov.uk/73BDA706D033977F0072CC449E2C63383E697AE6AB36CB086D1D17A72C56F4D4/7D264052E307D54846A037BDA1E04A19/LE35>,

If you get a SIMS error message when attempting to log in then the recent
client update has not been successful and you will need to reboot the
server.

If you are able to open SIMS.net please re-apply the latest SIMS client
update to the server and reboot again.

Hi Craig,

This is Vicky Moore’s CPOMS log in the incident we discussed earlier.
Please action:

In Computing yesterday, Nathan's log on screen was left with the Nirvana
logo on it, which he has set on his background.

Another student (Edward Alsop) reported after the end of the lesson to me
that Nathan had installed a browser to allow them to do this.

I reported this to IT and last night myself and Craig (IT) checked Nathan's
log in Impero.

Nathan had been using a web browser called Opera GX in his lessons which he
appears to have downloaded.

We were unsure how he had managed to do this (e.g. did he bring it in on a
memory stick) and so brought Nathan to the technicians room P1 today to
speak with him.

Nathan said he downloads the browser from a website in as he finds it
easier to use than Google, when we queried what in particular he was
unclear (lots of little things) and so we have asked him to write these
down if he remembers them so we can see if they can be installed on Google
which is fully monitored by Smooth wall. Nathan explained he had simply
been using the browser for class work, as he finds it easier. It also has
some games which are blocked on Google which he can access from this
browser (he knows he should not be on games too as I have spoken to him in
class about this before).

We have explained to Nathan how the monitoring works and shown him how this
logs everything, we have also explained why we were concerned as
potentially Opera is not monitored in quite the same way and so things
could be accessed which were not suitable in theory - he has been asked not
to use/install this any more in lessons. Craig also briefly explained some
online security to Nathan, such as being careful what you install and where
from as potentially could damage PCs/Network which is in breach of network
policy and also could be illegal.

With regards to his desktop, he said he was simply able to change this and
there were no restrictions - he was not sure how exactly but he said it was
something he did ages ago.

Logging for information - Nathan has been told he is not in trouble this
time as he does not appear to have done anything malicious from what he has
explained (apart from trying to access games occasionally which I always
ask him to turn off anyway).

He is interested in games design and wants to pursue this as a career in
the future.

I was unable to tag Craig Pritchard in perhaps as he works for Vital not
ASA?

The student’s name is Nathan Patterson.

Thanks
Lee

[required] Title: Having trouble with Chromebooks in Y4 at Deramore's
Description:
Hello Vital

The last two weeks we have had real problems with getting the class logged
on in Y4 at LDs, first lesson on Thursday both weeks - out of 30 kids we
had about 5 or 6 each week that it wouldn't log on even after several
attempts. Trying again 5 minutes later it worked for most of them, although
there was one kid that we were faffing about for about 10 minutes before
she finally got on!

We've also found that they were often having to refresh to get GClassroom
to load, and then in Purple Mash there were a few similar things - pages
needing to be refreshed to load properly etc. It isn't password mistakes -
the class teacher and I have both seen it happening, and checked the
usernames/passwords are correct! Mark said that they were getting 404
errors - not sure if that was at login, on going to classroom or when going
to purple mash or if it happened at all of those as I wasn't there when
that happened.

Today I used the same set of Chromebooks after playtime with the Y2 class,
across the corridor and all of them managed to get logged on, onto
classroom, and onto TTRS without seeming to have these issues - and last
week with the Y2s after play we did logging on, going to classroom, and
logging on to Purple Mash as in Y4 with no real issues.

I don't think the problem is user error - the Y4s are pretty competent,
apart from anything else! It doesn't seem to be affecting specific
children, or specific devices. It is really noticeable when getting all 30
logging on at the same time - it feels like a network/bandwidth problem.
I've not heard reports from any other classes - I don't know if there's
something specific about thursday mornings that means the network is
unusually contested, or if there could be a problem with an access point
that affects that classroom more than others?

It has led to a few rather challenging lessons in there - could someone
investigate please?

Thank you!
Kat

---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: Emma Duffield <emma@isoxford.com>
Date: Tue, 25 Jul 2023, 08:15
Subject: Upgrade news - Heritage Cirqa 5.7a and Look4 now available
To: d.rawling@gra.hlt.academy <d.rawling@gra.hlt.academy>


*Heritage Cirqa 5.7a is now available!*



Good morning all,

I am delighted to announce that the latest upgrade, Heritage Cirqa 5.7a, is
now available for download from our support website.



This upgrade is specifically for non-hosted Heritage Cirqa customers who
are currently on versions 5.6, 5.6a, or 5.6b.



Whilst the Heritage Cirqa upgrade itself is straightforward, it will
require some preparation from your IT colleagues. They will need to install
two important Windows components prior to running the upgrade (IIS URL
ReWrite and the .Net 6 hosting bundle). Full details of these, including
links to download them, are given in the upgrade helpsheet
https://cirqasupport.com/HI136.



There are some steps that you can do prior to the upgrade too – just a few
checks and housekeeping tasks. The instructions are in the helpsheet but
Tom is recording a short video and will upload it to
https://cirqasupport.com/VG56 later today.



*Should I apply the upgrade?*



I know that many of you are keen to get your hands on Look4. It is worth
mentioning, however that there will be at least one further upgrade
following on this summer as we add more functionality. If you work in an
academic library and staff are term-time only then you may decide to wait
until staff return and then apply whichever is the latest upgrade then, as
they will be cumulative. If you normally require IT assistance to run the
client as an administrator following the upgrade then you will need to do
this for the 5.7a upgrade.



Highlights of the upgrade are as follows:



*The new Look4 online catalogue interface*



There is lots to say about Look4 so please go to
https://cirqasupport.com/look4 for all the details. It is important to note
that you can continue to offer your users your existing Heritage Online
whilst you familiarise yourself with Look4 and populate the widgets with
your own content. There is no rush to switch to Look4; you can decide when
it's most convenient for you.



*Automatic index update*



Whether you use Heritage Online or Look4, your online catalogue will be
updated with new items as you catalogue them now, rather than being updated
on a scheduled basis. If you are doing lots of cataloguing you might wish
to temporarily turn this off – this can be set in the UPDATEINDEX
configuration value.



*Increased password security*



With the introduction of Look4, more secure reader passwords have been
introduced to replace the old reader PINs. If you are using single sign-on
you can continue to do so. If you are switching from PINs, however, the new
passwords are set by the reader via Look4 using the ‘Reset password’
option. If you would prefer to keep PINs for now you can set the new
KEEP.PINS configuration to Yes. Whatever the KEEP.PINS setting, the reader
will be able to use their old PIN until they change it via Look4, at which
point they will generate a new password and will no longer be able to use
their old PIN.



For a full list of the changes and fixes in version 5.7a please see
https://cirqasupport.com/HI137.



I hope you find this useful.



Best wishes,



Emma
